al competence among learners of Japanese as a second language. Qualitative data collected on learners studying abroad in Japan is evaluated to explain changes in their interactional competence and provides specific insights into the learning of Japanese. The situated analysis of multiple data sets generates meaningful interpretations of the development of interactional competence in the development of interactional competence and the learner-specific factors that shape developmental trajectories. Moreover, the context of the research provides insights into the types of learning resources and experiences that study abroad provides to assist learners’ in their progress towards becoming a competent speaker in the target community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish languagezJapan. 0aIntercultural communicationzJapan. 0aInterlanguage (Language learning)zJapan. 0aInterlanguage (Language learning). 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teachingzJapan. 0aLinguisticsxStudy and teachingzJapan. 0aPragmatics. 0aSecond language acquisitionzJapan. 0aSecond language acquisition. 0aSpeech acts (Linguistics)zJapan. 0aSpeech acts (Linguistics). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aCollaborative turn construction.  aInteractional competence.  aJapanese as a second language.  aJapanese learning and teaching.  aJapanese linguistics.  aJapanese speech style.  aSLA.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  aStudy abroad.  alearners studying abroad in Japan.1 aTaguchi, Naoko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z9783